1
00:00:10,053 --> 00:00:12,931
[electric buzzing]

2
00:00:15,350 --> 00:00:17,102
- [Sylvia] Hi, babe.
- Hi. Mmm. [kisses]

3
00:00:21,648 --> 00:00:23,400
[ticking]

4
00:00:28,280 --> 00:00:30,031
[ticking continues]

5
00:00:32,616 --> 00:00:33,993
- [knocking]
- Oh! Oh!

6
00:00:33,994 --> 00:00:36,495
I've still got 23 seconds left!

7
00:00:36,496 --> 00:00:39,332
- [timer bell dings]
- [beeping]

8
00:00:45,088 --> 00:00:46,715
[dance music playing]

9
00:00:49,593 --> 00:00:51,051
- [dance music ends]
- [knocking]

10
00:00:51,052 --> 00:00:52,345
One second, Simon!

11
00:01:01,187 --> 00:01:03,105
[yelling, grunting]

12
00:01:03,106 --> 00:01:04,689
- Awesome.
- [knocking]

13
00:01:04,690 --> 00:01:06,318
- [Sylvia] Okay.
- One minute!

14
00:01:07,485 --> 00:01:08,486
[grunts]

15
00:01:09,112 --> 00:01:10,572
Five minutes is up. Let's go.

16
00:01:11,990 --> 00:01:13,198
[mumbles]

17
00:01:13,199 --> 00:01:14,909
Hold on. [mumbles] Oh... Hold on.

18
00:01:14,910 --> 00:01:17,369
- [Maeve] Mmm.
- Okay. Hold on.

19
00:01:17,370 --> 00:01:18,787
[Maeve moans]

20
00:01:18,788 --> 00:01:20,290
[Sylvia] Oh, my God. Okay, great.

21
00:01:21,082 --> 00:01:23,584
Here. Let's get... That's dirty.

22
00:01:23,585 --> 00:01:26,087
Quick, quick, quick.
Quick sticks. Quick sticks.

23
00:01:27,339 --> 00:01:29,840
- Okay. Here we go.
- [Sylvia] Do you need this?

24
00:01:29,841 --> 00:01:31,592
- I'm seeing that house again today, babe.
- Right.

25
00:01:31,593 --> 00:01:32,885
The one with the five bathrooms?

26
00:01:32,886 --> 00:01:35,012
One for every single member
of this family.

27
00:01:35,013 --> 00:01:36,096
Can you imagine? I mean,

28
00:01:36,097 --> 00:01:37,765
I didn't know that was a thing.
It's like a château.

29
00:01:37,766 --> 00:01:39,475
We're gonna have more bathrooms
than we know what to do with.

30
00:01:39,476 --> 00:01:40,809
What do you care? You shit at work.

31
00:01:40,810 --> 00:01:42,478
- We don't say "shit."
- You're right, I'm sorry.

32
00:01:42,479 --> 00:01:45,689
Well, you know what? When we move,
I will shit at home like a king.

33
00:01:45,690 --> 00:01:46,899
Shit, shit, shit.

34
00:01:46,900 --> 00:01:48,984
- Don't say "shit."
- Where's the baguette?

35
00:01:48,985 --> 00:01:50,486
- What? What baguette?
- I need a baguette

36
00:01:50,487 --> 00:01:51,987
and a beret for French class.
Where are they?

37
00:01:51,988 --> 00:01:54,698
What? I... This is the first I've heard
about a baguette or a beret.

38
00:01:54,699 --> 00:01:56,075
- Oh, my God. Mom.
- What? I didn't...

39
00:01:56,076 --> 00:01:58,661
I didn't get an e-mail from Ms. Lauren.
Did you hear about the baguettes?

40
00:01:58,662 --> 00:02:00,162
- Sorry, I didn't. I gotta go.
- Or the beret?

41
00:02:00,163 --> 00:02:01,247
- Okay. See you.
- Good luck.

42
00:02:01,248 --> 00:02:02,873
- You can't close it because...
- I'm gonna fail!

43
00:02:02,874 --> 00:02:04,250
- Take this guy out.
- All right, buddy.

44
00:02:04,251 --> 00:02:07,587
- I am keeping it. I... I want it!
- Okay. But you cannot close your bag.

45
00:02:22,686 --> 00:02:26,730
- [Katie] So, how was your night with Will?
- It was fun for, like, 30 seconds.

46
00:02:26,731 --> 00:02:28,691
And then it just
turned into total drama again.

47
00:02:28,692 --> 00:02:30,985
We were literally screaming at each other

48
00:02:30,986 --> 00:02:32,653
on a street corner
at 1:00 a.m. in the morning.

49
00:02:32,654 --> 00:02:35,531
- Oh, my God. Just hearing that...
- [chuckles]

50
00:02:35,532 --> 00:02:37,700
...makes me feel more alive
than I have in 20 years.

51
00:02:37,701 --> 00:02:39,493
I need to start yelling more.

52
00:02:39,494 --> 00:02:40,911
- Yelling is so primal.
- I know.

53
00:02:40,912 --> 00:02:42,037
Nagging's not primal.

54
00:02:42,038 --> 00:02:44,331
No, it was... I'm not gonna lie,
it was a great night.

55
00:02:44,332 --> 00:02:46,584
- Mmm.
- But I can't... Like, honestly,

56
00:02:46,585 --> 00:02:48,919
I don't have enough time
for made-up problems in my life.

57
00:02:48,920 --> 00:02:51,797
I have enough real problems.
[inhales sharply] Like that one.

58
00:02:51,798 --> 00:02:55,551
I'm supposed to see that house today
in Encino for the third time.

59
00:02:55,552 --> 00:02:58,053
And I swear to God if I'm not gonna
buy it, she's gonna fire me.

60
00:02:58,054 --> 00:02:59,889
I told you not to hire Diane

61
00:02:59,890 --> 00:03:01,432
- as your Realtor.
- I know, I know.

62
00:03:01,433 --> 00:03:03,559
She's an office mom.
She's out of our league.

63
00:03:03,560 --> 00:03:05,352
She's wearing a fucking blazer.

64
00:03:05,353 --> 00:03:06,770
- I get it. You work in an office.
- Yeah.

65
00:03:06,771 --> 00:03:08,939
Some of us,
we're still stuck working at home.

66
00:03:08,940 --> 00:03:11,901
Just 'cause I wear sweatpants
doesn't mean I don't have an actual job.

67
00:03:11,902 --> 00:03:13,819
- She's too fancy for me. I know.
- Yeah.

68
00:03:13,820 --> 00:03:16,697
I know that.
If we weren't both parents here,

69
00:03:16,698 --> 00:03:19,158
there's no way she would ever
work with me in the first place.

70
00:03:19,159 --> 00:03:21,118
- Never.
- Hi!

71
00:03:21,119 --> 00:03:23,495
- Diane!
- Don't imitate... Don't imitate her face.

72
00:03:23,496 --> 00:03:26,040
- [gasps] Hi, Sylvia.
- Hi.

73
00:03:26,041 --> 00:03:29,501
[kisses] Such an exciting day.
We're putting an offer in.

74
00:03:29,502 --> 00:03:33,047
That's right. Today is totally about
buying a house with money.

75
00:03:33,048 --> 00:03:34,882
Because this one
put me through the wringer.

76
00:03:34,883 --> 00:03:36,175
- Guilty!
- We have looked at

77
00:03:36,176 --> 00:03:38,093
over 40 homes this year.

78
00:03:38,094 --> 00:03:39,887
- No.
- I sold Ellen and Portia their home

79
00:03:39,888 --> 00:03:41,388
in one day. [chuckles]

80
00:03:41,389 --> 00:03:43,807
- I heard good things about Ellen.
- Me too!

81
00:03:43,808 --> 00:03:45,684
I told her, "There are no shortcuts.

82
00:03:45,685 --> 00:03:48,229
You can't have square footage
and brand-spanking-new

83
00:03:48,230 --> 00:03:49,772
and location
all at a certain price point."

84
00:03:49,773 --> 00:03:52,024
I know. You were right.
You were right. I was wrong.

85
00:03:52,025 --> 00:03:55,361
And what she got
was an amazing fixer-upper.

86
00:03:55,362 --> 00:03:57,112
- It's...
- I mean, it's a project, to be sure.

87
00:03:57,113 --> 00:04:00,699
But now that the little one's in
kindergarten, it'll be a dream next act.

88
00:04:00,700 --> 00:04:02,868
I finally have the time to do it.

89
00:04:02,869 --> 00:04:05,037
So anyway, listen, ladies.
I'm gonna be late.

90
00:04:05,038 --> 00:04:07,831
I gotta get to Malibu
to show a beach compound.

91
00:04:07,832 --> 00:04:10,626
Can't say who it's for,
but it rhymes with Schminn Liesel.

92
00:04:10,627 --> 00:04:11,919
[both] Ooh!

93
00:04:11,920 --> 00:04:14,755
But I will be back in
the deep Valley to see you later.

94
00:04:14,756 --> 00:04:16,549
- Thank you, Diane. You're the best.
- [Diane] Bye-bye.

95
00:04:16,550 --> 00:04:18,592
Thank you for all your hard work,
your patience.

96
00:04:18,593 --> 00:04:19,969
- Good luck.
- You know what's crazy?

97
00:04:19,970 --> 00:04:21,220
Oh, my God.

98
00:04:21,221 --> 00:04:24,056
Schminn Liesel is actually the name
of my great-grandfather from Estonia.

99
00:04:24,057 --> 00:04:26,600
- No. No.
- <i>Papi</i> Schminn. Mm-hmm.

100
00:04:26,601 --> 00:04:27,685
[both chuckle]

101
00:04:27,686 --> 00:04:31,188
I thought Schminn Liesel was
the fifth child in the von Trapp family.

102
00:04:31,189 --> 00:04:33,023
- Oh, I've heard that. Yeah.
- Schminnie. Schminnie.

103
00:04:33,024 --> 00:04:34,943
- [phone ringing]
- Oh, dear.

104
00:04:37,821 --> 00:04:41,657
Ugh. So, what else?
We think of doing anything exciting today?

105
00:04:41,658 --> 00:04:43,993
- Oh, my God. It's a big one.
- Yeah. Walk me through it.

106
00:04:43,994 --> 00:04:46,370
Going to pick up
vaccination records for Sam.

107
00:04:46,371 --> 00:04:48,622
First sleepaway camp.
Yeah, it's pretty exciting. Yeah.

108
00:04:48,623 --> 00:04:50,874
- I just love days like these.
- Oh, you mean every day?

109
00:04:50,875 --> 00:04:52,168
- Oh, I do.
- [both chuckling]

110
00:04:57,382 --> 00:04:59,175
[phone ringing]

111
00:05:03,889 --> 00:05:07,391
<i>Hello, Sylvia. It's Will.
It's a terrible emergency.</i>

112
00:05:07,392 --> 00:05:08,685
<i>You have to call me.</i>

113
00:05:12,022 --> 00:05:13,356
[line ringing]

114
00:05:13,857 --> 00:05:14,899
What's the emergency?

115
00:05:14,900 --> 00:05:18,193
Uh, there's not actually an emergency.
I was just joking.

116
00:05:18,194 --> 00:05:19,361
<i>How you doing?</i>

117
00:05:19,362 --> 00:05:21,071
Okay. What... What do you want?

118
00:05:21,072 --> 00:05:22,740
Let's chat. What are you up to?

119
00:05:22,741 --> 00:05:24,658
[sighs] What... W-What's going on?

120
00:05:24,659 --> 00:05:28,996
Okay, fine. I'll tell you what's going on.
You, uh, left your credit card at my bar.

121
00:05:28,997 --> 00:05:30,205
Ah, fuck.

122
00:05:30,206 --> 00:05:31,749
If you wanted to hang out with me again,

123
00:05:31,750 --> 00:05:33,208
you didn't have to leave
some trinket behind.

124
00:05:33,209 --> 00:05:36,170
- You could've just asked me to lunch.
- I really... I don't have time for this.

125
00:05:36,171 --> 00:05:37,504
- So, lunch?
- No.

126
00:05:37,505 --> 00:05:38,547
- Brunch?
- No.

127
00:05:38,548 --> 00:05:41,508
Dim sum? That's my final offer.
You dim sum, you lose some.

128
00:05:41,509 --> 00:05:42,635
Okay. Goodbye, Will.

129
00:05:42,636 --> 00:05:45,471
Come on. Wait, wait, wait.
Don't you want your credit card back?

130
00:05:45,472 --> 00:05:48,641
You yelled at me on the street
in the middle of the night last night.

131
00:05:48,642 --> 00:05:51,936
Nobody treats me like that in my life
except for all three of my children.

132
00:05:51,937 --> 00:05:54,438
You yelled at me too.
We yell. People yell.

133
00:05:54,439 --> 00:05:57,524
We texted each other after.
It's fine, it's fine. It's all good.

134
00:05:57,525 --> 00:05:58,859
I'm over it. Get over it.

135
00:05:58,860 --> 00:05:59,945
You get over it.

136
00:06:04,908 --> 00:06:07,451
Well, the water's rising,
but I'm too afraid to flush it again.

137
00:06:07,452 --> 00:06:10,579
Uh, I don't know. Plunging might fix it,
it also might make it worse.

138
00:06:10,580 --> 00:06:12,665
Oh, yeah?
You should have a home repair show.

139
00:06:12,666 --> 00:06:14,667
[mumbles]
I'm so ready to leave this house.

140
00:06:14,668 --> 00:06:16,752
- You got this.
- Oh, my God. It's overflowing!

141
00:06:16,753 --> 00:06:18,420
- What'd you do?
- Nothing. I was just looking at it.

142
00:06:18,421 --> 00:06:22,508
Oh, no! It's everywhere.
Oh! Why is this my life? [yells]

143
00:06:22,509 --> 00:06:24,426
Uh, do you need me to come home?

144
00:06:24,427 --> 00:06:26,470
- <i>Bye.</i>
- Bye. Love you, babe.

145
00:06:26,471 --> 00:06:27,888
- [water bubbling]
- Toilet!

146
00:06:27,889 --> 00:06:30,350
[sighs] Fuck. Shit, shit. No! No!

147
00:06:31,643 --> 00:06:34,061
[groaning]

148
00:06:34,062 --> 00:06:36,022
- [doorbell rings]
- [knocking]

149
00:06:36,690 --> 00:06:38,357
- [doorbell rings]
- Fuck.

150
00:06:38,358 --> 00:06:40,485
- [knocking]
- Oh. [stammers] Coming!

151
00:06:42,946 --> 00:06:44,154
What are you doing here?

152
00:06:44,155 --> 00:06:46,949
- They call it "being a hero."
- [scoffs] I don't have time for this.

153
00:06:46,950 --> 00:06:49,660
I am a great man.
They will write songs about me.

154
00:06:49,661 --> 00:06:52,037
- What are you doing?
- I need your help. Can you come in here?

155
00:06:52,038 --> 00:06:54,583
[Will]
Can I grab some of these, uh, avocados?

156
00:06:55,500 --> 00:06:56,543
[Sylvia] Ugh.

157
00:06:57,210 --> 00:06:59,128
Oh, God. Oh, God.

158
00:06:59,129 --> 00:07:00,796
I promise you, it's just water.

159
00:07:00,797 --> 00:07:02,464
- Oh, yeah? Okay.
- Make it stop.

160
00:07:02,465 --> 00:07:04,009
I don't know how to make it stop.

161
00:07:04,593 --> 00:07:06,553
[Will] That ain't good. [chuckles]

162
00:07:07,095 --> 00:07:08,804
Did you do this? Was this you?

163
00:07:08,805 --> 00:07:10,181
- Could you just fix it?
- Yep.

164
00:07:11,182 --> 00:07:12,474
- There you go.
- [Sylvia] Ah.

165
00:07:12,475 --> 00:07:15,561
- Thank you. Thank you so much.
- There you go. Where's your mop?

166
00:07:15,562 --> 00:07:19,440
Uh, it's in the kitchen. But...
But you don't have to do that. [sighs]

167
00:07:19,441 --> 00:07:22,985
It's fine.
Like 60% of bartending is mopping.

168
00:07:22,986 --> 00:07:24,445
Thank you. You don't have to do that.

169
00:07:24,446 --> 00:07:26,155
Your house is very lovely. Very homey.

170
00:07:26,156 --> 00:07:27,364
You mean small.

171
00:07:27,365 --> 00:07:28,867
No, I mean very homelike.

172
00:07:29,534 --> 00:07:32,745
[Sylvia grunts]
Oh, my God. There's his iPad. Ugh.

173
00:07:32,746 --> 00:07:36,457
Oh. Secret iPad. Someone watching porno?

174
00:07:36,458 --> 00:07:37,959
- He's eight.
- And?

175
00:07:38,501 --> 00:07:40,794
When I was eight, I was disgusting.

176
00:07:40,795 --> 00:07:41,796
[Sylvia groans]

177
00:07:42,297 --> 00:07:44,298
- Don't put that in there. That's gross.
- Why?

178
00:07:44,299 --> 00:07:46,467
- Why is that gross?
- Because people lie down in there.

179
00:07:46,468 --> 00:07:48,886
- Not gross. You can drink toilet water.
- You could do a lot of things.

180
00:07:48,887 --> 00:07:50,387
- Exactly. Thirsty?
- Please take that...

181
00:07:50,388 --> 00:07:52,765
- You wanna suckle on the threads?
- Ew!

182
00:07:52,766 --> 00:07:53,807
[chuckles]

183
00:07:53,808 --> 00:07:56,602
What do you wanna do after this?
You wanna go to the beach?

184
00:07:56,603 --> 00:07:58,938
Get some oysters? Wanna go see a movie?

185
00:07:58,939 --> 00:08:03,317
I can't. I'm busy. I'm putting
an offer in on a house, actually.

186
00:08:03,318 --> 00:08:05,152
Yeah. After I do the final walk-through.

187
00:08:05,153 --> 00:08:06,862
Nice. What's wrong with this place?

188
00:08:06,863 --> 00:08:09,156
Oh, we've outgrown it.
It's too small for the five of us.

189
00:08:09,157 --> 00:08:11,617
There's one bathroom.
It's... And... Which is flooding.

190
00:08:11,618 --> 00:08:13,202
- Tell me about the new place.
- It's great!

191
00:08:13,203 --> 00:08:16,205
It's, um, you know, fixer-upper.
Needs a bit of work.

192
00:08:16,206 --> 00:08:17,665
[gasps] Can I come on the walk-through?

193
00:08:17,666 --> 00:08:18,624
- No.
- Please.

194
00:08:18,625 --> 00:08:20,334
Please.
I'm actually very good with renovations.

195
00:08:20,335 --> 00:08:22,294
- Since when?
- I redid most of the bar by myself.

196
00:08:22,295 --> 00:08:23,212
Really?

197
00:08:23,213 --> 00:08:25,214
Yeah. It was a chicken slaughterhouse
when we got it.

198
00:08:25,215 --> 00:08:26,799
- Get out.
- Yeah.

199
00:08:26,800 --> 00:08:29,261
- Wow.
- We still find feathers and beaks.

200
00:08:29,761 --> 00:08:33,097
I know. Seriously, though. Can I come?
I'll be very helpful, I promise.

201
00:08:34,224 --> 00:08:36,307
Okay. Just don't talk.

202
00:08:36,308 --> 00:08:37,560
- I won't.
- Don't...

203
00:08:37,561 --> 00:08:39,436
Just don't talk to me or anybody.

204
00:08:39,437 --> 00:08:41,689
- No talking. Perfect.
- Nope.

205
00:08:41,690 --> 00:08:43,900
So, how often do you see Audrey?

206
00:08:44,484 --> 00:08:47,027
Um, I don't know. Every few weeks.

207
00:08:47,028 --> 00:08:50,781
I, uh... I still have a bunch of stuff
I haven't moved out of the house.

208
00:08:50,782 --> 00:08:53,993
So, you know, I'm periodically
going back there to get some shit.

209
00:08:53,994 --> 00:08:55,287
What? Why?

210
00:08:55,912 --> 00:08:57,997
Just... You know.
Takes a long time to move.

211
00:08:57,998 --> 00:08:59,456
Uh, you can do it in a day.

212
00:08:59,457 --> 00:09:02,127
[scoffs] It's not just the stuff,
you know. Gandalf is still there.

213
00:09:03,169 --> 00:09:05,129
- Audrey has Gandalf?
- Yeah.

214
00:09:05,130 --> 00:09:07,798
But he was yours first.
You love that lizard.

215
00:09:07,799 --> 00:09:10,968
I still love Gandalf. It's just...
She insisted on keeping him

216
00:09:10,969 --> 00:09:14,179
'cause she didn't think I was
responsible enough to take care of him.

217
00:09:14,180 --> 00:09:16,432
Well, that's ridiculous. [chuckles]

218
00:09:16,433 --> 00:09:19,685
He's like your son in lizard form.
You should have custody.

219
00:09:19,686 --> 00:09:22,813
I have joint custody,
'cause I go see him all the time.

220
00:09:22,814 --> 00:09:24,774
- [scoffs]
- What?

221
00:09:25,483 --> 00:09:28,027
- What? You can tell me. Tell me.
- Nothing. I just... I don't know.

222
00:09:28,028 --> 00:09:31,864
It's hard to recover from a divorce
if your lives are still totally entwined.

223
00:09:31,865 --> 00:09:34,992
Well, divorce is a messy thing.
It's not like one day you're married,

224
00:09:34,993 --> 00:09:36,953
the next day
you never see each other again.

225
00:09:37,996 --> 00:09:41,123
Have you ever thought
that you leave your stuff there

226
00:09:41,124 --> 00:09:44,251
and she keeps Gandalf
